    allDay: true,
    location: "NAIFA",
    status: "completed",
    description: "Framing: With long-term care costs increasing across homecare and assisted living services, potentially draining the financial legacy seniors intend to transfer to the next generation. \r\n\r\nMaking matters worse, many clients avoid long-term care considerations because they don’t think they’ll need it. This increased risk makes it more important than ever for financial professionals and insurance agents to discuss long-term care coverage and how it can help protect their financial legacy transfer.\r\nFinancial literacy: While it generally improves with age, it can decline in older age due to cognitive issues.\r\n\r\nFinancial security: Many older adults rely heavily on Social Security, and some face challenges such as debt and limited savings. • SME: Frank Tebyani (AmeriLife)",
